# By deafult, Mode restricts (or limits) the number of rows the SQL query returns to 100. You can undo this by
# checking the "Limit 100" box next to "Run".

# Many analysts use limits as a simple way to keep their queries from taking too long to return. For example, if
# you just wanted to scan the first few rows of data to get an idea of which fields you care about and how you 
# want to manipulate them, you don't want to end up waiting a long time for all of your results to be displayed
# because you didn't use a limit.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Using the LIMIT command

# You can limit the number of rows your SQL query returns by using the following syntax:

SELECT *
  FROM tutorial.us_housing_units
 LIMIT 100
 
# This does the same thing as having the "Limit 100" box checked.

___________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

# Practice Problem 1

# Write a query that uses the LIMIT command to restrict the result set to only 15 rows.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# My answer

SELECT *
  FROM tutorial.us_housing_units
 LIMIT 15
 
